    keywords: ["SQL", "NoSQL", "ACID", "BASE", "schema", "scaling", "joins"],
    explanation:
      "**SQL Databases (e.g., PostgreSQL, MySQL)**\n- **Data model**: Tables with rows and columns; relationships via foreign keys.\n- **Schema**: Rigid, predefined, with data types and constraints. Altering schema can be costly.\n- **ACID compliance**: Guarantees atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability – ideal for financial systems, inventory, order management.\n- **Joins**: Rich support for combining tables via foreign keys; complex queries possible.\n- **Scaling**: Primarily vertical (more powerful server). Horizontal scaling (sharding) is possible but more complex (e.g., Citus for PostgreSQL).\n- **Consistency**: Strong consistency by default (though isolation levels can be adjusted).\n\n**NoSQL Databases (MongoDB, Redis, Cassandra, Neo4j)**\n- **Data model**: Varies – document (JSON), key‑value, wide‑column, graph.\n- **Schema**: Flexible or schema‑less – each record can have different fields. Easy to iterate.\n- **Consistency model**: Often BASE (Basically Available, Soft state, Eventual consistency). Prioritizes availability and partition tolerance over immediate consistency (CAP theorem).\n- **Joins**: Typically no or limited joins; data is denormalized or embedded.\n- **Scaling**: Designed for horizontal scaling (sharding, replication) across commodity servers.\n- **Use cases**: High‑volume real‑time apps (social media, IoT, caching, catalogs) where strict consistency is less critical.\n\n**Trade‑offs summarized**\n| Aspect | SQL (PostgreSQL) | NoSQL (e.g., MongoDB) |\n|--------|----------------|----------------------|\n| Schema | Fixed, enforced | Dynamic, flexible |\n| Integrity | Strong (FK, constraints) | Application‑enforced |\n| Transactions | ACID, multi‑row | Limited (single document in many) |\n| Scaling | Vertical (simpler) / Horizontal (complex) | Horizontal (native) |\n| Query power | SQL (declarative, powerful) | Proprietary, less expressive |\n\n**PostgreSQL note**: With JSONB, foreign data wrappers, and extensions like `pg_shard` (Citus), PostgreSQL blurs the line – you can get document flexibility while keeping ACID and joins. This makes it a “polyglot” database.",
