    expected:
      "Denormalization is the intentional addition of redundant data to a normalized database to improve read performance (query speed) or simplify complex joins. It is used in reporting, data warehousing, high‑traffic read‑heavy systems, and when join performance becomes a bottleneck. Trade‑off: increased storage, update anomalies, and slower writes.",
    keywords: [
      "denormalization",
      "redundancy",
      "performance",
      "read-heavy",
      "join",
      "materialized view",
    ],
    explanation:
      "**What is denormalization?** It is the reverse of normalization: combining tables or duplicating columns to reduce the number of joins required for common queries. While normalized schemas (3NF) excel at write consistency and data integrity, they can become slow for complex analytical queries or high‑throughput read operations.\n\n**When to use denormalization**\n1. **Reporting / Data Warehousing**: Star schemas with fact tables and dimension tables are denormalized (e.g., storing product name and category in the fact table) to speed up aggregation.\n2. **High‑traffic web applications**: Reading a user’s profile together with their latest order summary might require joining 4–5 tables. Denormalizing key fields into a single table can reduce latency.\n3. **Caching layers**: Materialized views or Redis caches are essentially denormalized snapshots.\n4. **Time‑series data**: Storing pre‑computed aggregates (daily totals) alongside raw data.\n5. **When joins are too expensive**: On very large tables (billions of rows) even indexed joins become costly.\n\n**Techniques for denormalization in PostgreSQL**\n- **Add redundant columns**: E.g., store `user_name` in the `orders` table so you don’t need to join `users`.\n- **Pre‑computed aggregates**: Maintain a `user_stats` table with `order_count`, `total_spent` updated via triggers or `REFRESH MATERIALIZED VIEW`.\n- **Materialized views**: `CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW sales_summary AS SELECT ...` with refresh on schedule.\n- **JSONB embedding**: Store related child data as a JSONB array in the parent row (e.g., an order with its line items embedded).\n\n**Risks**\n- Update anomalies: changing a user’s name requires updating all denormalized copies.\n- Increased storage.\n- Slower writes (must update redundant copies).\n- Complexity in application logic.\n\n**Best practice**: Start normalized, profile queries, and denormalize only when performance testing proves a bottleneck. Use triggers or materialized views to keep redundancy under control.",
    code: "-- Normalized: need join every time\nSELECT u.name, o.total FROM orders o JOIN users u ON o.user_id = u.id;\n\n-- Denormalized: store user_name in orders\nALTER TABLE orders ADD COLUMN user_name TEXT;\n-- Then query directly\nSELECT user_name, total FROM orders;\n-- But now update anomaly: when user changes name, must update all orders.\n\n-- Safer denormalization: materialized view\nCREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW order_user_summary AS\nSELECT o.id, o.total, u.name FROM orders o JOIN users u ON o.user_id = u.id;\nREFRESH MATERIALIZED VIEW CONCURRENTLY order_user_summary;",
